04402nam a22004575i 9780226798028DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212003ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226798028  a(DE-B1597)575548  a(OCoLC)1243312128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBD494 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a113/.091 aBrague, Rémi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wisdom of the World :bThe Human Experience of the Universe in Western Thought /cRémi Brague. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (306 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tTranslator’s Note -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Setting the stage -- t1. Prehistory: A Pre-Cosmic Wisdom -- t2. The Birth of the Cosmos in Greece -- tPart II. Four Models -- t3. Socrates’ Revolution; Plato’s Restoration -- t4. The Other Greece: The Atomists -- t5. Other than Greece: The Scriptures -- t6. The Other Other: Gnosticism -- tPart III. The medieval model -- t7. Marginal Models -- t8. The Standard Vision of the World -- t9. An Ethical Cosmos -- t10. A Cosmological Ethics -- t11. Abrahamic Excess -- tPart IV: The new World -- t12. The End of a World -- t13. An Impossible Imitation -- t14. The Lost World -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the ancient Greeks looked up into the heavens, they saw not just sun and moon, stars and planets, but a complete, coherent universe, a model of the Good that could serve as a guide to a better life. How this view of the world came to be, and how we lost it (or turned away from it) on the way to becoming modern, make for a fascinating story, told in a highly accessible manner by Rémi Brague in this wide-ranging cultural history. Before the Greeks, people thought human action was required to maintain the order of the universe and so conducted rituals and sacrifices to renew and restore it. But beginning with the Hellenic Age, the universe came to be seen as existing quite apart from human action and possessing, therefore, a kind of wisdom that humanity did not. Wearing his remarkable erudition lightly, Brague traces the many ways this universal wisdom has been interpreted over the centuries, from the time of ancient Egypt to the modern era. Socratic and Muslim philosophers, Christian theologians and Jewish Kabbalists all believed that questions about the workings of the world and the meaning of life were closely intertwined and that an understanding of cosmology was crucial to making sense of human ethics. Exploring the fate of this concept in the modern day, Brague shows how modernity stripped the universe of its sacred and philosophical wisdom, transforming it into an ethically indifferent entity that no longer serves as a model for human morality. Encyclopedic and yet intimate, The Wisdom of the World offers the best sort of history: broad, learned, and completely compelling. Brague opens a window onto systems of thought radically different from our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  acosmology, history, ethics, philosophy, ritual, sacrifice, gods, divinity, ceremony, mythology, folklore, modernity, morality, wisdom, sacred, kabbalah, judaism, religion, spirituality, theology, christianity, ancient egypt, islam, socrates, hellenism, greece, universe, knowledge, plato, gnosticism, scriptures, atomists, bible, medieval, nonfiction.1 aFagan, Teresa Lavender.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226798028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226798028/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles